{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_TV0EFJL7tl73ShNj1aObAqug","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tinput:\n3\t  query: string\n4\t  attachmentIds: array\n5\t---\n6\t\n7\tBuild a complete, openable live-project app from supplied material — as a PLAN → per-item BUILD\n8\tpipeline, so no single model turn has to author a whole app at once. First read the attachments, then\n9\tmake a holistic plan of the app (its tables, endpoints, reusable components, and MULTIPLE pages). From\n10\tthere each category is a `plan → implement` pair that the host fans out one file at a time: plan the\n11\ttables → write each table (with its source-derived rows), plan the endpoints → write each typed API,\n12\tplan the components → write each reusable component, plan the pages → write each page (which imports\n13\tthe components and reads the endpoints). A final node writes the persistent chat layout and reports\n14\twhat was built. Every write is its own bounded node, so a slip on one file no longer loses the build;\n15\teach writer returns `{ ok, error? }` and validates at write time. Pages use `@app/runtime` data hooks\n16\tand `@lmthing/css` design tokens only.\n17\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_tPb0UsB1toyLruNLs583FlmL","session_id":"9c7a9dc1-bb8c-4315-b194-e357aac0f2c7","uuid":"8c0162c7-e5a1-4604-8d8e-901be8518024","timestamp":"2026-07-16T18:28:49.570Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace endpoint build failure"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_lFcnCNHRsgr4vCse2vQYnnLu","type":"tool_result","content":"55\t\n56\t**GROWING an app is not done until the new section serves a PAGE.** When you ADD to an app that already\n57\thas pages, a set of `writeProjectTable`s is only the DATA MODEL, not a usable section: with no\n58\t`writeProjectPage`, `/app/<project>/` shows the user nothing new. So finish in the SAME turn — after the\n59\ttables, author the page(s) backed by a `writeProjectApi` that reads the REAL rows — and you ADD a\n60\tsection without rewriting the existing home (see \"GROWING an app that already exists\" below).\n61\t\n62\t**MAKE IT OPENABLE EARLY — order matters, because you can run out of turn.** (This applies to the\n63\tfreeform GROW path — the first whole-app build goes through the `build_live_project` tasklist above,\n64\twhich owns its own openable boundary.) When you GROW an app freeform, a big addition (many tables, a\n65\tlarge attached file, a lot of rows to seed) can consume your whole turn on DATA and leave you reporting\n66\t\"all tables created and seeded!\" with no page ever written. That is the same empty-app failure, arrived\n67\tat by running long rather than by forgetting — and it is worse, because you sound finished. So do NOT\n68\tleave the page to the end. As soon as the FIRST new table exists, author its page and the\n69\t`writeProjectApi` behind it; then go back and add the remaining tables, seed the rest of the rows, and\n70\tgrow the section to surface them as you go. Judge it by what the user gets if you are cut off at any\n71\tmoment: a page over three of the seven tables is something they can open and use, and you can always\n72\tseed more later. Seven perfectly seeded tables and no page is nothing they can open. **Openable first,\n73\tcomplete second.**\n74\t\n75\t## Ground rules — author DIRECTLY (do not explore)\n76\t\n77\tAuthor DIRECTLY from the request — do not go hunting through files first. NEVER reference a variable\n78\tyou did not declare — a stray bare word (`rootEntries`, `projectFiles`, a random name) is a\n79\ttypecheck error that ABORTS your turn before any write lands.\n80\t\n81\tTo check what ALREADY EXISTS in the project, use the PROJECT-ROOTED reads:\n82\t`listProjectDir('database')` / `listProjectDir('hooks')` / `listProjectDir('events')` — list the\n83\tauthored files (a missing dir returns `entries: []`), and `readProjectFile('database/<name>.json')`\n84\treads a file's text. These resolve against THIS project.\n85\t\n86\t**Field names differ by reader — do NOT mix them up (this is the #1 recovered typecheck error):**\n87\t`readProjectFile(path)` returns `{ ok, content }` → read the file body from **`.content`**.\n88\t`readDocument(id)` (an ATTACHMENT) returns `{ ok, text }` → read the file body from **`.text`**.\n89\t`listProjectDir(dir)` returns `{ ok, entries }` → the file list is in **`.entries`**. Using\n90\t`readProjectFile(...).text` is a typecheck error (`Property 'text' does not exist on type\n91\t'{ ok; content; error }'`) that aborts your turn — it is ALWAYS `.content` for a project file.\n92\t\n93\tThere is NO generic filesystem here — `execShell`, `ls`, `readFile`, `readFileRaw`, `glob`, and\n94\t`grep` do not exist for you (a call fails typecheck and aborts your turn). Inspect the project ONLY\n95\tthrough the project-rooted reads above; persist ONLY through the `writeProject*` writers. This is by\n96\tconstruction: the typed writers are your entire vocabulary, and they cannot mis-root. `db` is always\n97\tavailable to you (you hold the grant): on a project with no tables yet `db.tables()` returns `[]`\n98\t(it never throws), and a MUTATING verb (`db.insert`/`db.update`/`db.remove`) throws a clear\n99\t`project \"…\" has no database yet — author a table first` until the first `writeProjectTable` lands.\n100\tSo the order is: `writeProjectTable` (creates the table + seeds any rows) FIRST, then `db.*` reads\n101\tand updates work against it. Keep each statement small and self-contained — declare every identifier\n102\tyou use.\n103\t\n104\tWrite file source with the `[ 'line1', 'line2', … ].join(\"\\n\")` array pattern so the file has REAL\n105\tline breaks — NEVER a single string with literal `\\n` escapes (that writes a one-line file the\n106\tloader can't parse: `Syntax error \"n\"`). The `writeProject*` writers now REJECT unparseable source\n107\t(`{ ok:false, error:'source failed to parse…' }`); if you see that, fix the escape/quote and write\n108\tagain — never leave a broken file behind.\n109\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_tPb0UsB1toyLruNLs583FlmL","session_id":"9c7a9dc1-bb8c-4315-b194-e357aac0f2c7","uuid":"bfc947ef-d788-4f9f-92e5-23babcaac9c8","timestamp":"2026-07-16T18:28:49.571Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace endpoint build failure"}
