{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_dU82Wjpzb9vFSQ0IrNiCP0Px","type":"tool_result","content":"125\t\n126\t**A. A step FAILS** → stop the run at that step (the rest would run on corrupted state). Then:\n127\t  1. **Attribute before you touch anything.** FIRST `git diff` the file you would fix — a prior\n128\t     invocation may have left an UNCOMMITTED change already addressing this exact behavior. If the\n129\t     instruction ALREADY says the right thing (e.g. \"each distinct part gets its own specialist,\n130\t     brevity is not a merge\") and the step STILL fails the same way, L1 is exhausted — do NOT add a\n131\t     fourth sentence saying the same thing louder. That standing-but-ineffective prose is proof the\n132\t     cause is structural: CLIMB (see the L2 note below). Then re-run the failing turn as a minimal\n133\t     one-shot probe on a clean project, to place it on the ladder:\n134\t     - Same ask phrased DIRECTLY authors cleanly, but the in-persona phrasing didn't → **L1** (the\n135\t       brain judged / routed badly).\n136\t     - The agent tried the right thing but a call THREW or failed TYPECHECK → the primitive is\n137\t       missing / too weak → **L2 or L3**, never a prompt.\n138\t     - The `expect` was wrong or the message truly ambiguous → **L0**. Do not weaken a real assertion\n139\t       to go green.\n140\t     - **A clean direct probe does NOT prove L1.** \"The primitive can do it when asked directly\" only\n141\t       rules out L2/L3 for a *one-shot capability* failure. It does NOT rule out L2 when the real-path\n142\t       behavior is UNRELIABLE or SYSTEMATICALLY wrong: L2 is not only \"the primitive is missing,\" it is\n143\t       also \"the current STRUCTURE doesn't reliably drive the primitive.\" If the same step fails the\n144\t       same way across two independent replays — and especially if it drops the SAME items each time\n145\t       (systematic, not random) — a third prose tweak will not fix it. That repetition is the ladder\n146\t       telling you to CLIMB. Before you touch prose again, TRACE two things: (a) WHERE the wrong\n147\t       decision is actually made (the caller's payload, or the specialist's own design node?), and\n148\t       (b) WHAT INPUT it saw (a decision made on a lossy summary that never contained the dropped\n149\t       items is fixed by changing the INPUT or adding an enumeration STEP, never by exhorting the\n150\t       agent to try harder). A free-form judgment that must come out the same every time wants a\n151\t       DETERMINISTIC structure — an enumerate-then-`forEach` tasklist node that lists the parts as\n152\t       discrete items and builds one per item — which is an **L2** artifact that does not exist yet.\n153\t  2. **Fix at the LOWEST rung that truly fixes it** (ladder below). Land it in SOURCE, rebuild,\n154\t     restart the local server so the tree is adopted.\n155\t  3. **Verify with a fresh rerun.** New directory / project / DB / spaces, from step 1, forward\n156\t     THROUGH the previously-failed step. The moment that step (and everything before it) passes,\n157\t     STOP — do not go on to later steps; that is the next invocation's job. A from-scratch replay is\n158\t     the only thing that proves a shared `instruct.md` change didn't regress an earlier step.\n159\t  4. **If the fix does not verify:** revise and rerun a COUPLE more times (≈2–3 total). If that step\n160\t     still won't go green, STOP and report the still-failing state honestly — do not grind your\n161\t     context to dust chasing it. A later invocation, with fresh context, tries again.\n162\t\n163\t**B. Every step PASSES (no failure)** → the scenario is fully green → **author ONE extension** to it\n164\t  per `extend.md` (add steps reaching an untouched capability, same persona), and STOP. Do NOT run\n165\t  the new steps this invocation — the next invocation runs them.\n166\t\n167\t# The fix ladder — take the lowest rung; prove you can't stay lower\n168\t\n169\t**L0 SCENARIO** — the assertion / message was wrong. Fix `scenario.yaml`. Guard: you are not lowering\n170\ta bar the product actually failed.\n171\t\n172\t**L1 PROMPT** — the artifact exists, it just decided / said the wrong thing (most failures). Name\n173\tWHICH: agent `instruct.md` (act vs answer vs delegate vs refuse; three-store routing; research vs\n174\tquery) · `charter.md` (fork-safe guardrail) · a tasklist task `NN-<id>.md` (its INSTRUCTION, or its\n175\tFRONTMATTER: `role` / `functions` / `canDelegateTo` / `capabilities` / `output` / `dependsOn` /\n176\t`forEach` / `condition` — never forbid a tool in prose, gate it in frontmatter) · a tasklist\n177\t`index.md` · `knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md` · a space function's body. Fix as a GENERAL\n178\tPRINCIPLE a competent colleague would agree with; ZERO scenario literals (persona name, fixture\n179\tcontents, this scenario's table names — in instruction OR example) — that is overfitting and fails.\n180\t**And ZERO scenario-DOMAIN framing** — a grep for literals won't catch it, but a travel scenario's fix\n181\tthat reasons about \"itineraries\" / \"destinations\", a cooking one about \"recipes\" / \"ingredients\", a\n182\tclinic one about \"patients\", is overfit just the same: it bends a system-wide brain toward this one\n183\tstory's domain. Write the domain-NEUTRAL principle (the failure here — merging a small part into a\n184\tcatch-all — generalizes as \"brevity is not a reason to merge; a distinct part with few facts still gets\n185\tits own specialist\"). Before you land an L1 edit, ask: could this exact sentence have come from a\n186\tscenario in a completely different domain? If not, rewrite it until it could.\n187\t\n188\t**L2 STRUCTURE MISSING** — expressible today, but the artifact doesn't exist. Add it, inside the\n189\tspace format (no core change): a new AGENT · a new TASKLIST or TASK NODE · a new SPACE FUNCTION · a\n190\tnew capability grant or `canDelegateTo` edge on an existing agent · **a new KNOWLEDGE DOMAIN the agent\n191\tloads on demand** (`loadKnowledge('<domain>','<field>','<option>')` reads\n192\t`<space>/knowledge/<domain>/<field>/<option>.md`, always injected, no capability needed).\n193\t> **When a recurring JUDGMENT is unreliable as inline prompt prose — how to classify / partition /\n194\t> route a KIND of material — do not write the rule a fourth time in the agent's brain. Move the\n195\t> heuristic into loadable domain KNOWLEDGE and keep the prompt minimal: classify the material's\n196\t> domain, `loadKnowledge` the guide for that domain, apply it.** This is how the organize-material\n197\t> partition was finally fixed: `user-thing/knowledge/organizing/split/{index,default,trips,\n198\t> household,vehicles,pets,…}.md` — a general life-domain library — with `01-inventory` reduced to\n199\t> \"load the menu, load the matching domain guide(s), split by it.\" The knowledge must be GENERAL\n200\t> (many domains, each phrased for ALL instances of that domain) and carry **ZERO scenario literals**\n201\t> (no persona/place/fixture) — a domain-keyed knowledge base is the RIGHT home for domain-flavored\n202\t> guidance that would be overfitting inside a system-wide prompt. A partition/classification rule\n203\t> that keeps failing as prose is itself the signal to climb to this rung.\n204\t\n205\t**L3 FRAMEWORK GAP** — today's primitives CANNOT express it, and you can point at where a lower rung\n206\twould go and show it has no way to say the thing. A core change (`sdk/org/libs/core|cli/**`), held to\n207\tthe runtime discipline:\n208\t- a new or improved FRONTMATTER FIELD on an agent / task, when no field says it; OR\n209\t- a new GLOBAL + capability + DTS + injection + fork-intersection, when the model surface lacks the\n210\t  power; OR\n211\t- a change to the turn loop / fork / tasklist orchestrator / typecheck.\n212\tShips LOCKSTEP (not-granted ⇒ not-injected ⇒ absent from the DTS ⇒ a clean typecheck error), WITH a\n213\ttest that would have caught the gap, and the matching `org/docs/` page updated in the SAME change\n214\t(`pnpm docs:check` is a hard gate). L3 is heavy and it is the judge's most dangerous power — enter it\n215\tonly on proof, and flag it loudest of all in the report so the human reviewing knows a framework\n216\tchange is in the diff.\n217\t\n218\t> **RUN the test, and prove it is LOAD-BEARING — a written-but-unrun test is not a fix.** After you\n219\t> add it: `cd sdk/org && pnpm test <path>` must PASS with your change, and — the step people skip —\n220\t> must FAIL when you revert your change (stash the one edit, run, confirm red, restore). This is your\n221\t> cheapest, context-cheapest proof and it catches two real failure modes at once: a fix that doesn't\n222\t> actually work, and a test that passes no matter what (mock that never exercises the changed leg).\n223\t> Do this BEFORE the full scenario rerun — the rerun is expensive and can exhaust your context, so a\n224\t> green revert-test is what lets you report an L3 fix with confidence even if the rerun gets cut short."}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"call_tPb0UsB1toyLruNLs583FlmL","session_id":"9c7a9dc1-bb8c-4315-b194-e357aac0f2c7","uuid":"07ce7830-76cd-47d1-8e91-ef2f884c3d63","timestamp":"2026-07-16T18:31:32.659Z","subagent_type":"Explore","task_description":"Trace endpoint build failure"}
