{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"call_OvS50877zwyUtIhEezaMXVS0","type":"tool_result","content":"1\t---\n2\tid: implement_endpoints\n3\toutput:\n4\t  route: string\n5\t  name: string\n6\t  ok: boolean\n7\tdependsOn: [plan_endpoints, plan_tables, implement_tables]\n8\tforEach: plan_endpoints.endpoints\n9\trole: general\n10\tfunctions: []\n11\t---\n12\t\n13\tWrite ONE typed API handler into the LIVE project's `api/`. Your endpoint is in `item` =\n14\t{ name, route, purpose, tables }: `item.name` is the stable id the plan assigned, and `item.route`\n15\talready encodes the method last (e.g. `cost-lines/GET`). `plan_tables.tables` (the real schemas being\n16\twritten) is in scope — read its columns so your query and `Output` type match real data. Write the\n17\tFULL endpoint ESM module inline with the array-`join(\"\\n\")` pattern (real line breaks): it MUST export\n18\t`name` set to `item.name` VERBATIM (the stable id the page passes to `useApi` — do NOT re-derive it\n19\tfrom the route or transform it; without the exact match the loader rejects the whole app), a\n20\t`description`, an `Input` interface, an `Output` interface, and a default `async (input, ctx) => Output`\n21\thandler that reads/writes through `ctx.db` (`await ctx.db.query/insert/update/remove`). Every read\n22\tendpoint returns `{ items: [...] }`; keep that exact envelope even for contacts, summaries, or grouped\n23\tdata, because pages consume planned endpoints as `data.items`. `writeProjectApi` returns `{ ok, error? }`\n24\tand validates the module at write time; rewrite and retry if `w.ok` is false. Emit one statement:\n25\t\n26\t```typescript\n27\tconst ep = item;\n28\tconst name = ep.name;\n29\tconst table = Array.isArray(ep.tables) && ep.tables[0] ? ep.tables[0] : (plan_tables.tables[0] ? plan_tables.tables[0].name : 'items');\n30\tconst src = [\n31\t  \"export const name = '\" + name + \"';\",\n32\t  \"export const description = '\" + String(ep.purpose).replace(/'/g, '') + \"';\",\n33\t  \"export interface Input {}\",\n34\t  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n35\t  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n36\t  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('\" + table + \"');\",\n37\t  \"  return { items };\",\n38\t  \"}\",\n39\t].join(\"\\n\");\n40\tconst w = writeProjectApi(ep.route, src);\n41\tcurrentTask.resolve({ route: ep.route, name, ok: w.ok });\n42\t```\n43\t"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"9c7a9dc1-bb8c-4315-b194-e357aac0f2c7","uuid":"06b7d01e-45fb-421d-8b6e-d400dea73f7e","timestamp":"2026-07-16T18:32:20.589Z","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/home/vasilis/LMTHING/lmthing/sdk/org/libs/core/system-spaces/system-appbuilder/tasklists/build_live_project/06-implement_endpoints.md","content":"---\nid: implement_endpoints\noutput:\n  route: string\n  name: string\n  ok: boolean\ndependsOn: [plan_endpoints, plan_tables, implement_tables]\nforEach: plan_endpoints.endpoints\nrole: general\nfunctions: []\n---\n\nWrite ONE typed API handler into the LIVE project's `api/`. Your endpoint is in `item` =\n{ name, route, purpose, tables }: `item.name` is the stable id the plan assigned, and `item.route`\nalready encodes the method last (e.g. `cost-lines/GET`). `plan_tables.tables` (the real schemas being\nwritten) is in scope — read its columns so your query and `Output` type match real data. Write the\nFULL endpoint ESM module inline with the array-`join(\"\\n\")` pattern (real line breaks): it MUST export\n`name` set to `item.name` VERBATIM (the stable id the page passes to `useApi` — do NOT re-derive it\nfrom the route or transform it; without the exact match the loader rejects the whole app), a\n`description`, an `Input` interface, an `Output` interface, and a default `async (input, ctx) => Output`\nhandler that reads/writes through `ctx.db` (`await ctx.db.query/insert/update/remove`). Every read\nendpoint returns `{ items: [...] }`; keep that exact envelope even for contacts, summaries, or grouped\ndata, because pages consume planned endpoints as `data.items`. `writeProjectApi` returns `{ ok, error? }`\nand validates the module at write time; rewrite and retry if `w.ok` is false. Emit one statement:\n\n```typescript\nconst ep = item;\nconst name = ep.name;\nconst table = Array.isArray(ep.tables) && ep.tables[0] ? ep.tables[0] : (plan_tables.tables[0] ? plan_tables.tables[0].name : 'items');\nconst src = [\n  \"export const name = '\" + name + \"';\",\n  \"export const description = '\" + String(ep.purpose).replace(/'/g, '') + \"';\",\n  \"export interface Input {}\",\n  \"export interface Output { items: any[] }\",\n  \"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\",\n  \"  const items = await ctx.db.query('\" + table + \"');\",\n  \"  return { items };\",\n  \"}\",\n].join(\"\\n\");\nconst w = writeProjectApi(ep.route, src);\ncurrentTask.resolve({ route: ep.route, name, ok: w.ok });\n```\n","numLines":43,"startLine":1,"totalLines":43}}}
