able = Array.isArray(ep.tables) && ep.tables[0] ? ep.tables[0] : (plan_tables.tables[0] ? plan_tables.tables[0].name : 'items');\\nconst src = [\\n  \\\"export const name = '\\\" + name + \\\"';\\\",\\n  \\\"export const description = '\\\" + String(ep.purpose).replace(/'/g, '') + \\\"';\\\",\\n  \\\"export interface Input {}\\\",\\n  \\\"export interface Output { items: any[] }\\\",\\n  \\\"export default async function handler(_input: Input, ctx: { db: any }): Promise<Output> {\\\",\\n  \\\"  const items = await ctx.db.query('\\\" + table + \\\"');\\\",\\n  \\\"  return { items };\\\",\\n  \\\"}\\\",\\n].join(\\\"\\\\n\\\");\\nconst w = writeProjectApi(ep.route, src);\\ncurrentTask.resolve({ route: ep.route, name, ok: w.ok });\\n```\\nContext variables (available in scope):\\n- query: \\\"Organize this Tanzania trip material into a live app the user can open on their phone. It spans: (1) a detailed trip itinerary/plan with traveler names, dates, route, and logistics from tanzaniamemories.md, (2) a cost spreadsheet with all expenses from trip-costs.xlsx, (3) official Ngorongoro park-fee rules and tariffs from the PDF, (4) a personal memory photo from Stone Town, Zanzibar, and (5) facts from a crater-day voice memo (transcribed below). Build per-topic specialist spaces for each distinct domain (Tanzania logistics, safari park rules, Zanzibar, trip costs/finances) and then build the app itself with tables for itinerary items, costs, park fees, contacts, and memories, seeded with all the extracted data. The app needs pages the user can actually browse on a phone — an itinerary view, a cost tracker with totals, a park-fee reference, and a memories/photo gallery.\\\\n\\\\nBuild the complete live-project app now: write source-derived tables and rows, then write the project API and openable pages that show those rows.\\\\n\\\\nSource summary:\\\\n5 attachments: a trip-plan Markdown file (tanzaniamemories.md) with the full Aug 3–20 itinerary, route, and contacts; a cost spreadsheet (trip-costs.xlsx) with all expenses; a Ngorongoro Conservation Area park-fee PDF with official tariffs; a Stone Town courtyard photo; and a transcribed voice memo from Ngorongoro crater day recounting Emmanuel the driver, bracelet purchases for Athena (~$20–25 / TSH 35,000), an extra ranger tip of TSH 5,000 not previously budgeted, and a reminder to ask Richard about it before the safari balance payment.\\\\n\\\\nFacts available only from image/audio analysis:\\\\nVOICE MEMO TRANSCRIPT (crater day): Driver guide Emmanuel (not Richard from the office) was excellent, really knowledgeable. At the rim, a Maasai lady sold two beaded bracelets bought for Athena Mari — paid roughly TSH 35,000 (about $20–25), exact amount uncertain. Emmanuel mentioned an extra ranger tip sometimes expected at the gate: TSH 5,000 cash, separate from park fees — nobody told us about this before. Need to ask Richard about it before the safari balance payment. IMAGE DESCRIPTION: The Stone Town photo shows the inside of a bright courtyard or atrium in a multi-story building, looking upward at white stucco walls, arched windows, and several dark wooden balconies with decorative lattice railings — a personal memory shot from Zanzibar.\\\\n\\\\nSpecialist build results:\\\\n[{\\\\\\\"topic\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Tanzania Safari Logistics & Itinerary\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"ok\\\\\\\":true,\\\\\\\"errors\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"topic\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Ngorongoro Conservation Area Park Fees & Tariffs\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"ok\\\\\\\":true,\\\\\\\"errors\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\"},{\\\\\\\"topic\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"Zanzibar & Stone Town\\\\\\\",\\\\\\\"ok\\\\\\\":true,\\\\\\\"errors\\\\\\\":\\\\\\\"\\\\\\\"}]\\\"\\n- attachmentIds: [\\\"1b63a08b-4317-4c75-8c63-8b4215e13a1c\\\",\\\"38f22d9c-af45-4ca3-a750-350af0ebb5bb\\\",\\\"7fbb3093-a986-49f4-b345-0c3bc3997493\\\",\\\"1ea0f451-3cd2-459e-8a5c-0138828014eb\\\"]\\n- item: {\\\"name\\\":\\\"itinerary-detail\\\",\\\"route\\\":\\\"itinerary/[id]/GET\\\",\\\"purpos